# Fix Rope X-Alignment Logic

## Changes
Modified [UI/MainForm.cs](file:///d:/Full_end/C%23/ArtaleAI/UI/MainForm.cs) to handle rope approaches more safely.

### [UI/MainForm.cs](file:///d:/Full_end/C%23/ArtaleAI/UI/MainForm.cs)
- Increased the distance threshold for switching from generic "Move To" behavior to specialized "Climb Rope" behavior from **2.0px** to **10.0px**.
- This change prevents the character from overshooting the rope using generic movement (which has higher speed/inertia) and allows the dedicated `RopeAlignmentController` to take over earlier for precise, tapped alignment.

```csharp
// Before
if (distanceToRopeX > 2.0f) { ... MoveToTargetAsync(..., 2.0f); }

// After
if (distanceToRopeX > 10.0f) { ... MoveToTargetAsync(..., 10.0f); }
```

## Verification
- **Scenario**: Character moving towards a rope at X=100 from X=150.
- **Previous Behavior**: Character runs (MoveTo) until X=102. If inertia carries it to X=98, it corrects back. Oscillations or falls could occur. Precise alignment only triggered if it miraculously stopped between 98.5 and 101.5.
- **New Behavior**: Character runs (MoveTo) until X=110. It stops (or hands off). Then [ClimbRopeAsync](file:///d:/Full_end/C%23/ArtaleAI/Services/CharacterMovementController.cs#631-834) starts. It detects distance=10px (>1.5px), so it calls `AlignToRopeAsync`. This function uses precise key taps to nudge user to X=100 +/- 1.5px, then climbs.

This should eliminate the "not checking X alignment" issue by enforcing a dedicated check and alignment phase.
